When you call `fmt::format` with `const char*` and `T` arguments, and if `T` is not formattable, then it will go here:
```cpp
template <typename T, typename Char = char, typename Enable = void>
struct fallback_formatter {
  static_assert(
      no_formatter_error<T>::value,
      "don't know how to format the type, include fmt/ostream.h if it provides "
      "an operator<< that should be used");
};
```
and trigger the `static_assert`, which is not a SFINAE-able error.  Furthermore, if we try putting it in a `decltype` like so:
```cpp
using Test = decltype( fmt::format( "{}", std::declval<MyType>() ) );
```
The line always compiles, for any type, and `Test` is `std::string` (so again this is not SFINAE-friendly).

My use case is that I need to be able to write something like this in my code:
```cpp
MyClass m;
if constexpr( is_formattable<MyClass> ) {
  fmt::print( "{}", m );
}
```
Any way that this could be made possible?

